args: Greetings, my lady. You look exquisite.\nMight I have the honor of this dance?
My apologies—I'm afraid the only pleasure\nI'm interested in sharing tonight is rapport.\nAnd I have my eye on someone already.
(There he is: Count Delchi. I have to cozy\nup to him and retrieve the necklace\nsomehow.)
(All before the sun sets, no less.)
So you fancy the Count, hm?\nI would advise you reconsider.
He is a man of great education whose\nheart lies only with those possessed of\nconsiderable intellectual stature.
We ought to get on splendidly, then.\nI will go and introduce myself.
Bah! This dreadful fracas has yet to provide\nme with even the barest shred of dignified\ndiscourse! Surrounded by fools, I am!
How do you do, Count? Might I bend your\near for the briefest of moments?
My identity matters not. ＂To lay a lady's\nsecrets bare is an act of violence, for 'tis\nfar more charming she remain an enigma.＂

Why, I'd recognize lines from 'The Devil's
Bowman' anywhere! You are indeed a
woman of taste to quote such a masterful
opera!
Oho ho. Your compliments suit me, sir.\nPray tell me, which works stir YOUR heart?

More than opera, my true passion is for
literature. I am particularly smitten of late
by a work called 'Edea's Tears.' Surely
you've had the pleasure?

Ah, yes. A work by the philosopher Codrus.
I believe the famed passage is, ＂mourning
the world aloud is the only way to change
it.＂
Oho! You've a discerning eye indeed!
＂To speak with gentlemen of quality, dig\nyour well of knowledge both broad and\ndeep.＂ My mother taught me this.
I would speak with you at greater length,\nCount. Surely we could parley on any\nnumber of riveting subjects, no?
But of course. 'Tis a delight to discover you\nare not some mere fool in costume. Butler!
Yes, Master. Here are your beverages.
Let us drink before we speak.\nTo the meeting of two intellectuals!
Indeed. To meeting a Count of quality.
I cannot believe you can speak at such\nlength. Ha ha ha! What an auspicious\nmeeting this is.
I am no match for you, my lord. You are\na paragon of refinement and taste.
And this manor, decorated with such first-\nrate art—it's more museum than home.\nYou make a fine curator indeed.

Oho, and you have aesthetic sense, too!
Collecting art is my passion. What I have
displayed here is but a portion of my
collection.

My most exquisite treasures are housed
within a room deeper inside my manor.
I've just added to it a most stunning
necklace of Eastern origin! Gah ha ha!
Gracious! Tell me, Count, would you honor\nme with a tour of this room?
(Yes! That necklace is so close I can taste\nit...not that I'm in any hurry to do so.)
And now, I present to you:\nmy collection room.
It's pitch-black, my lord.\nIs your collection really here?
Of course. And what I've collected...is you!

Despite my appearance, I possess some
knowledge of the magical arts. I've
bewitched you with a marvelous spell to
help you relax.
Clearly you and I have a different\ndefinition of ＂marvelous.＂
Hm. It would seem you've managed to\nresist it somewhat. But how will you fare\nagainst THIS?
Butler, put her in the usual place.\nAnd after that... Geh heh heh...
*gasp* Where in the world am I?\nBrr, it's freezing.
Rise and shine, my sweet kitten.\nHow are you feeling?
I must say, this does not rank highly\namong my favorite wake-up calls. You've\nbound this rope too tight for my liking.
Oh, how I love a woman with some bite!
Flattery will get you nowhere, I'm afraid.\nMore importantly, where are we?
A storage shed on the grounds of my\nmanor. Or at least, that's what it appears\nto be! It is actually my secret workshop!
A workshop for what, pray tell?
I told you my passion is collecting works\nof art. That was a lie.
I will one day sell the art I have amassed\nand use the resulting sum to bribe the\nEmpress, assuring my rise in the world.
You've yet to demonstrate surpassing\nambition yourself. And in truth, my sights\nextend far beyond mere oil on canvas.
My true passion is for ice sculpture.\nTo that end, I use my magic to keep my\nworkshop as cold as a snowy mountain.
I slowly freeze my guests in here,\nturning them into exquisite depictions\nof the human form!
Intellectuals, frozen in ice, bearing\nanguished expressions of utter despair!\nI am not a purveyor of art, but misery!
I've dealt with a lot of men in my time,\nbut never one as utterly perverse as you.
Ha ha ha! Truly, you honor me!
Now, the hour has already grown late.\nI must see my party guests off.
It's HOW late? Wait! Has the sun set?!
Long before you roused from your slumber.
(On top of being kidnapped by this\nperverse old man, it's long past the time\nI agreed upon with Valyx! This is bad!)
